{
  "analysis": "We reviewed eval.py and the reference MJCF model. eval.py compares the final full physics state of model.xml against model_ref.xml after simulating for total_sim_time=2.0 seconds using each model's own timestep, and then measures average simulation time over 20 runs. It requires the tuned model to run at 60% of the reference model's time or less while matching the final state within atol=1e-5 and containing no NaN/Inf. The initial attempt copied model_ref.xml to model.xml, which yielded a zero state difference but would not meet the speed requirement. The model_ref.xml does not specify timestep, so it uses MuJoCo's default timestep (likely 0.002 s). To reduce simulation time without changing physical properties, the most appropriate change is to increase the timestep in model.xml. Since the number of integration steps scales inversely with timestep (nstep = total_sim_time / timestep), achieving a time pctg of 0.6 requires setting timestep >= 0.003333... s. We'll try slightly above that (e.g., 0.0034) to ensure the threshold is met while testing correctness. This change does not alter physical properties of the bodies; it only changes numerical integration resolution. If correctness fails, we will adjust the timestep downward until it passes while still trying to meet the 60% time target.",
  "plan": "1) Confirm there is no <option> timestep in model.xml. 2) Insert an <option timestep=\"0.0034\"/> element near the top-level to increase timestep. 3) Verify the change in model.xml. 4) Run eval.py to test correctness and speed. 5) If correctness fails, reduce timestep (e.g., 0.00335 or 0.00333) and retest; if speed is insufficient, adjust upward carefully until both constraints are satisfied.",
